{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_bath_ver01/data/sn92063852/00279551321/1958030801/0350.xml":{"full_text":"Business Slump\u2014\n(Continued from Bock Pago)\nMany a time I have insisted that the cyclkal pattern of\nour great business growth is deeply woven Into our economic\nfabric. This cyclical pattern cannot be changed.\nThe simple facts of the recent boom and the current\nrecession are:\n(1) At the end of the war we had great shortages el ram\nmaterials, production and labor.\n(2) This was accompanied by voracious appetites for all\nkinds of gimmicks, both necessities and luxuries..\n(3) For more than ten years, in order to satisfy these\ndemands, plant expansion and production proceeded at an\nabnormal rate, which could not by the very nature of things\ncontinue forever. The longer the abnormality continued the\nmore certain it became that we would run into a catching\nup period, hence this recession.\n(4) We must now digest or wear out some of the excess\nproduction of goods.\n(5) Os great importance is the fact that now that produc\ntion has passed consumption, business will reduce its expen*\nditures for plant and equipment expansion. The extraordi\nnary expenditure of the last years for plant expansion is\none of the chief sustaining factors of the great boom.\n(6) Ultimate increese in production, even above the\nlevels of the mid-1950 s is practically certain. But we must\ncatch yp first. *e* speg|\n(7) This catching up will probably not occur during the\nnext two or three months as some of our economists want\nto believe. It would take an economic miracle for consump*\ntion fully to catch up with production facilities in less than\ntwo or three years.\n(8) However, in a previous letter, I have insisted that\nthis recession is very likely to be abnormally short as com*\npared with other recessions that have followed great boom\nperiods. This is because so many new frontiers of invention\nand new fields of activity are opening up before us.\nWHILE THIS RECESSION SHOULD BE SHORT, so far\nas historical comparisons are concerned, it does not mean\nthat it may not qet worse, as to employment, business profit*,\nand particularly the stock market. The stock market does\nnot seem to have given full effect as yet to the current or\npossible early future statistics of this business recession.\nI don't believe that the time has arrived yet to adventure\ninto common stock commitments.\nThomas F. Willmor#\nAmericans United\u2014\n(Continued from Back Page)\nm\n(Excerpts Reprinted from\nFREEDOM AND SEPARATION\nPublished by the Detroit Chapter of POAU,\nAmericans United for Separation of Church and'State,\n22482 Alexander Drive, St. Clair Shores, Mich.\nVolume 2, Number 2 March, 1958)\nDR. HUGH R. FARRELL\nIn 1934, after graduating from college, he entered\nthe noviciate of the Order of Our Lady of Mount Carmel\n(Discafcedh A year later he made his simple profession of\nvow fend was sent to Oklahoma City monastery to continue\nhis theological studies. After making his solemn profession\nin 1938 he received Minor Orders, and the subdiaconate,\nfrom Bishop Francis K. Kelly of Oklahoma City.\nThe following two years were beset with doubts concern\ning the validity of many of the claims of the Roman Catholic\nChurch, and so in 1940 he applied for, and received from\nRome, a dispensation of his solemn vows and left the Order\nand the Roman Catholic Church. He entered the Protestant\nministry and during World War II he was one of the non-\nCatholic chaplains at Texas A. and M. College. In 1955 he\njoined the staff of Christ's Mission and it is through them\nthat he comes as our chapter meeting speaker.\nHe was a Roman Catholic for twenty-nine years, six of\nwhich were spent as a monk of the Discalced Carmelite\nOrder. With this background, Rev. Farrell is particularly\nqualified to speak on the subject, \"The Vatican's Position\n(Continued Next Column Top)\nGait\u2019s Eraayvlist\nHilly Graham\nSUNDAYS, 3:30, WXYZ; 10 P.M., CKLW\nSee